“proper  officer”  means  the  officer  or  person  appointed  by  or 
under  any  written  law  relating  to  an  election  to  be  in  charge,  or 
to  have  the  conduct,  thereof;

(a)  knowingly makes any false statement on or in connection 
with  any  application  to  be  placed  on  any  register  of 
electors;

(b)  forges  or  fraudulently  defaces  or  fraudulently  destroys 
any  nomination  paper,  or  delivers  to  a  returning  officer 
any  nomination  paper  knowing  the  same  to  be  forged;

(c)  forges or counterfeits or fraudulently defaces or fraudulently 
destroys  any  ballot  paper  or  the  official  mark  on  any 
ballot  paper;

(e)  sells  or  offers  to  sell  any  ballot  paper  to  any  person  or 
purchases  or  offers  to  purchase  any  ballot  paper  from 
any  person;

(f)  not  being  a  person  entitled  to  be  in  possession  of  any 
ballot paper which has been marked with any authorized 
mark  has  any  such  ballot  paper  in  his  possession;

(h)  without  due  authority  takes  out  of  the  polling  station 
any ballot paper or is found in possession of any ballot 
paper  outside  a  polling  station;

(j)  without  due  authority  prints  any  ballot  paper  or  what 
purports  to  be  or  is  capable  of  being  used  as  a  ballot 
paper  at  an  election;

(d)  wilfully  prevents  any  person  from  voting  at  the  polling 
station  at  which  he  knows  or  has  reasonable  cause  to 
believe  such  person  is  entitled  to  vote;

(b)  communicate to any person at any time any information 
obtained  at  those  proceedings  as  to  the  number  of  the 
ballot  paper  sent  to  any  person;

(a)  commits  the  offence  of  personation,  or  aids,  abets, 
counsels  or  procures  the  commission  of  the  offence 
of  personation;

(a)  appoint every polling agent, counting agent, clerk and 
messenger employed, whether for payment or not, on 
behalf  of  the  candidate;

(d)  use any dwelling house, shop house, hut, hall or any 
premises  as  an  office  or  a  centre  of  any  political 
party  in  the  constituency;

(a)  to patrol, and to monitor the activities of the candidates, 
in its area of control to ensure that written laws relating 
to  elections  are  being  complied  with;

(b)  that  such  candidate  and  his  election  agent  took  all 
reasonable  means  for  preventing  the  commission  of 
corrupt  and  illegal  practices  at  such  election;

(a)  that general bribery, general treating or general intimidation 
have so extensively prevailed that they may be reasonably 
supposed  to  have  affected  the  result  of  the  election;

